WEBVTT

00:00:00.792 --> 00:00:03.045 align:middle line:90%


00:00:00.792 --> 00:00:03.045 align:middle line:84%
Is it time to get high
in Trump's America?

00:00:03.045 --> 00:00:04.046 align:middle line:90%
That's into the Buzzsaw.

00:00:04.046 --> 00:00:09.426 align:middle line:90%
[THEME MUSIC]

00:00:17.434 --> 00:00:18.936 align:middle line:84%
>> SEAN STONE:
Welcome to "Buzzsaw,"

00:00:18.936 --> 00:00:21.271 align:middle line:84%
where we cut through the
mainstream narrative to explore

00:00:21.271 --> 00:00:22.356 align:middle line:90%
the hidden truths.

00:00:22.356 --> 00:00:23.815 align:middle line:10%
I'm your host, Sean Stone.

00:00:23.815 --> 00:00:25.234 align:middle line:10%
And with me today
is David Seaman,

00:00:25.234 --> 00:00:27.694 align:middle line:10%
who is a reporter and former
contributor to Huffington

00:00:27.694 --> 00:00:29.446 align:middle line:10%
Post and Business Insider.

00:00:29.446 --> 00:00:32.406 align:middle line:10%
He also has his own YouTube
channel, DavidSeamanOnline,

00:00:32.406 --> 00:00:35.244 align:middle line:10%
and today he gives us some
insight into his research.

00:00:35.244 --> 00:00:37.329 align:middle line:84%
So I actually want to
start by asking you--

00:00:37.329 --> 00:00:39.706 align:middle line:84%
because online it's
very scandalous,

00:00:39.706 --> 00:00:41.833 align:middle line:84%
the fact that Huffington
Post basically cut you off

00:00:41.833 --> 00:00:43.460 align:middle line:84%
as a contributor,
as I understand it

00:00:43.460 --> 00:00:46.046 align:middle line:84%
because you were questioning
Hillary Clinton's health

00:00:46.046 --> 00:00:47.422 align:middle line:90%
issues before the election.

00:00:47.422 --> 00:00:49.258 align:middle line:84%
>> DAVID SEAMAN: Yeah,
Sean, that's correct.

00:00:49.258 --> 00:00:51.426 align:middle line:10%
I had a contributorship
there, and they cut off

00:00:51.426 --> 00:00:54.513 align:middle line:10%
my access and my
contributorship shortly

00:00:54.513 --> 00:00:56.807 align:middle line:10%
after a story about her
alleged health problems

00:00:56.807 --> 00:00:59.893 align:middle line:10%
hit their home page, because
they have a trending component,

00:00:59.893 --> 00:01:02.229 align:middle line:10%
and the top stories
rank right there

00:01:02.229 --> 00:01:04.105 align:middle line:10%
on the front page
of Huffington Post.

00:01:04.105 --> 00:01:06.900 align:middle line:84%
Mine was the top story
in the overnight.

00:01:06.900 --> 00:01:09.403 align:middle line:84%
When somebody woke up in the
morning, they didn't like that,

00:01:09.403 --> 00:01:12.364 align:middle line:84%
and that was the end of my
Huffington Post chapter.

00:01:12.364 --> 00:01:14.783 align:middle line:84%
>> SEAN: So, needless to
say that Huffington Post was

00:01:14.783 --> 00:01:17.577 align:middle line:84%
basically biased in
terms of their stand.

00:01:17.577 --> 00:01:18.578 align:middle line:90%
>> SEAMAN: I believe so.

00:01:18.578 --> 00:01:19.997 align:middle line:90%
I believe it was biased.

00:01:19.997 --> 00:01:21.914 align:middle line:84%
And I wasn't even
really using my column

00:01:21.914 --> 00:01:23.500 align:middle line:90%
to promote political ideology.

00:01:23.500 --> 00:01:26.920 align:middle line:84%
It was mostly stuff about
cryptocurrency and gold

00:01:26.920 --> 00:01:28.714 align:middle line:90%
ownership, Bitcoin.

00:01:28.714 --> 00:01:30.549 align:middle line:84%
But then there was
this viral video

00:01:30.549 --> 00:01:33.343 align:middle line:84%
that Paul Watson had
put out about the claims

00:01:33.343 --> 00:01:36.513 align:middle line:84%
about her health being much
poorer than people thought,

00:01:36.513 --> 00:01:38.432 align:middle line:90%
and I just linked to that.

00:01:38.432 --> 00:01:40.600 align:middle line:84%
And on the basis of
that, I was removed.

00:01:40.600 --> 00:01:41.435 align:middle line:90%
>> SEAN: Yeah.

00:01:41.435 --> 00:01:42.811 align:middle line:84%
I want to get into
it more later,

00:01:42.811 --> 00:01:45.564 align:middle line:84%
but I certainly think it's
indicative to me of the idea

00:01:45.564 --> 00:01:48.692 align:middle line:84%
that the fake news is not
really just in the alt media.

00:01:48.692 --> 00:01:50.985 align:middle line:84%
Sure, there are fake news
stories going through the alt

00:01:50.985 --> 00:01:53.113 align:middle line:84%
media, but it's also the
mainstream media, I think,

00:01:53.113 --> 00:01:55.324 align:middle line:90%
that has not only--

00:01:55.324 --> 00:01:56.700 align:middle line:84%
there's a phoniness
to it, there's

00:01:56.700 --> 00:01:59.661 align:middle line:84%
also just an overall suspicion
I think that people have,

00:01:59.661 --> 00:02:03.123 align:middle line:84%
and rightfully so, of their
mainstream news sources because

00:02:03.123 --> 00:02:06.043 align:middle line:84%
of stories like yours, where
you're being axed, essentially,

00:02:06.043 --> 00:02:08.336 align:middle line:90%
for just raising questions.

00:02:08.336 --> 00:02:09.378 align:middle line:90%
>> SEAMAN: Yeah, exactly.

00:02:09.378 --> 00:02:12.507 align:middle line:84%
I think people want the
news, not the narrative.

00:02:12.507 --> 00:02:15.344 align:middle line:84%
And the Huffington
Post and a number

00:02:15.344 --> 00:02:16.720 align:middle line:84%
of other big
titles, some of them

00:02:16.720 --> 00:02:20.557 align:middle line:84%
on the right-- not all of them
are left-wing publications.

00:02:20.557 --> 00:02:23.226 align:middle line:84%
They have money, and they
have seemingly credible names,

00:02:23.226 --> 00:02:24.895 align:middle line:84%
but they're doing
exactly what you said.

00:02:24.895 --> 00:02:26.521 align:middle line:90%
They're promoting fake news.

00:02:26.521 --> 00:02:29.066 align:middle line:84%
It's not simply the
small independents.

00:02:29.066 --> 00:02:31.109 align:middle line:90%
It's also the big corporations.

00:02:31.109 --> 00:02:32.944 align:middle line:84%
And I think President
Trump to an extent

00:02:32.944 --> 00:02:36.156 align:middle line:84%
has found a workaround, which
is you just yell "fake news,"

00:02:36.156 --> 00:02:38.367 align:middle line:84%
and you point at the
person who's doing it.

00:02:38.367 --> 00:02:40.577 align:middle line:84%
And some of the
claims I make online

00:02:40.577 --> 00:02:42.913 align:middle line:84%
are pretty big,
controversial claims,

00:02:42.913 --> 00:02:44.456 align:middle line:84%
but it's always
sourced to something

00:02:44.456 --> 00:02:46.625 align:middle line:84%
that I believe in,
so either a Wikileaks

00:02:46.625 --> 00:02:48.960 align:middle line:84%
email or a firsthand
source who's

00:02:48.960 --> 00:02:50.504 align:middle line:90%
willing to go on the record.

00:02:50.504 --> 00:02:52.714 align:middle line:84%
I don't believe in things
like, oh, someone told me--

00:02:52.714 --> 00:02:54.007 align:middle line:90%
I can't tell you who it is.

00:02:54.007 --> 00:02:56.885 align:middle line:84%
There was this thing on the back
of a napkin, and I oversaw it.

00:02:56.885 --> 00:02:59.054 align:middle line:84%
That's not my style
of journalism.

00:02:59.054 --> 00:03:00.931 align:middle line:84%
And yet the
mainstream media, they

00:03:00.931 --> 00:03:03.183 align:middle line:84%
conduct that style of
journalism, where they say,

00:03:03.183 --> 00:03:06.686 align:middle line:84%
hey, we have unnamed sources
saying A, B, and C. No, no, no,

00:03:06.686 --> 00:03:08.230 align:middle line:84%
you don't get to
use unnamed sources.

00:03:08.230 --> 00:03:09.481 align:middle line:90%
We don't get that luxury.

00:03:09.481 --> 00:03:10.649 align:middle line:90%
Why do you?

00:03:10.649 --> 00:03:12.109 align:middle line:90%
And we're seeing a lot of that.

00:03:12.109 --> 00:03:14.236 align:middle line:84%
>> SEAN: Yeah, that was
always sort of the luxury

00:03:14.236 --> 00:03:18.407 align:middle line:84%
of the investigative
journalists,

00:03:18.407 --> 00:03:22.244 align:middle line:84%
was that they basically were
able to have their unnamed

00:03:22.244 --> 00:03:25.329 align:middle line:84%
sources, but because oftentimes
their editor knew who it was

00:03:25.329 --> 00:03:27.791 align:middle line:84%
and there was a notion that
there was establishment press--

00:03:27.791 --> 00:03:30.544 align:middle line:84%
the idea was "The Washington
Post" and "The New York Times,"

00:03:30.544 --> 00:03:34.923 align:middle line:84%
these editors were respected,
and they would know who

00:03:34.923 --> 00:03:37.216 align:middle line:84%
the source are and make
sure the story was vetted.

00:03:37.216 --> 00:03:38.844 align:middle line:84%
>> SEAMAN: We can no
longer trust that.

00:03:38.844 --> 00:03:39.553 align:middle line:90%
>> SEAN: Exactly.

00:03:39.553 --> 00:03:40.470 align:middle line:84%
I don't know that
you ever could,

00:03:40.470 --> 00:03:42.514 align:middle line:84%
because I think it was always
essentially an establishment

00:03:42.514 --> 00:03:43.473 align:middle line:90%
perspective.

00:03:43.473 --> 00:03:46.101 align:middle line:84%
Guys like Sy Hersh have always
been great journalists as far

00:03:46.101 --> 00:03:47.853 align:middle line:84%
as having challenged
the establishment

00:03:47.853 --> 00:03:50.272 align:middle line:84%
and done it repeatedly, so
that gives them credibility.

00:03:50.272 --> 00:03:51.773 align:middle line:84%
But on the whole,
I think we've seen

00:03:51.773 --> 00:03:54.276 align:middle line:84%
a lot of the feeling of the
establishment press basically

00:03:54.276 --> 00:03:56.570 align:middle line:84%
serving the establishment
point of view.

00:03:56.570 --> 00:03:59.072 align:middle line:84%
And now we're entering a
world where people obviously

00:03:59.072 --> 00:04:01.533 align:middle line:84%
don't need to turn to CNN
or Fox News or "New York

00:04:01.533 --> 00:04:03.326 align:middle line:84%
Times" or "Washington
Post" for their news.

00:04:03.326 --> 00:04:05.412 align:middle line:84%
They're getting their news
from a whole collection

00:04:05.412 --> 00:04:07.622 align:middle line:84%
of sources, which is
both-- let's be honest.

00:04:07.622 --> 00:04:09.791 align:middle line:84%
It's both dangerous
and positive.

00:04:09.791 --> 00:04:11.251 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I see it
all the time where

00:04:11.251 --> 00:04:13.378 align:middle line:84%
people are spouting
things, and it's like,

00:04:13.378 --> 00:04:15.338 align:middle line:84%
you just saw someone's
YouTube video,

00:04:15.338 --> 00:04:17.257 align:middle line:84%
and there's no
journalism behind it.

00:04:17.257 --> 00:04:19.301 align:middle line:84%
It's just literally
their perspective.

00:04:19.301 --> 00:04:25.265 align:middle line:84%
And so in a sense, how
do we navigate for truth

00:04:25.265 --> 00:04:30.353 align:middle line:84%
in what is becoming a
very post-factual reality?

00:04:30.353 --> 00:04:33.482 align:middle line:84%
>> SEAMAN: I think we're moving
towards trusting individuals

00:04:33.482 --> 00:04:35.525 align:middle line:90%
more than trusting these names.

00:04:35.525 --> 00:04:38.528 align:middle line:84%
So you mentioned an
individual you trust.

00:04:38.528 --> 00:04:41.198 align:middle line:84%
I think we're going to see more
of that, where I'll say, look,

00:04:41.198 --> 00:04:43.950 align:middle line:84%
I think Glenn Greenwald is a
good reporter when it comes

00:04:43.950 --> 00:04:45.869 align:middle line:90%
to national security stuff.

00:04:45.869 --> 00:04:47.370 align:middle line:84%
And I can say that
it doesn't matter

00:04:47.370 --> 00:04:49.539 align:middle line:84%
if he's working at "The
Guardian" or "The Intercept"

00:04:49.539 --> 00:04:50.373 align:middle line:90%
or somewhere else.

00:04:50.373 --> 00:04:52.876 align:middle line:84%
It's that name that
remains credible, until he

00:04:52.876 --> 00:04:54.002 align:middle line:90%
kind of blows his cover.

00:04:54.002 --> 00:04:56.213 align:middle line:84%
If he does something that
turns out to be false,

00:04:56.213 --> 00:04:58.590 align:middle line:84%
then the public should not
trust him as much anymore.

00:04:58.590 --> 00:05:01.259 align:middle line:84%
But since he really hasn't,
he has a lot of my trust,

00:05:01.259 --> 00:05:02.552 align:middle line:90%
and the same with Wikileaks--

00:05:02.552 --> 00:05:05.430 align:middle line:84%
10 years of publishing
actual e-mails.

00:05:05.430 --> 00:05:08.016 align:middle line:84%
Not a single one has
been a fake or a fraud,

00:05:08.016 --> 00:05:09.434 align:middle line:90%
so they have a lot of my trust.

00:05:09.434 --> 00:05:11.728 align:middle line:84%
And other independent
journalists, I think,

00:05:11.728 --> 00:05:12.854 align:middle line:90%
should feel the same way.

00:05:12.854 --> 00:05:14.439 align:middle line:84%
Unless they breach
that trust, there's

00:05:14.439 --> 00:05:16.775 align:middle line:84%
no reason not to
trust Wikileaks.

00:05:16.775 --> 00:05:19.528 align:middle line:84%
There's no reason not
to trust Glenn Greenwald

00:05:19.528 --> 00:05:20.737 align:middle line:90%
or other individuals.

00:05:20.737 --> 00:05:23.406 align:middle line:84%
There is reason not to trust
"The Washington Post"--

00:05:23.406 --> 00:05:24.783 align:middle line:90%
the change in ownership.

00:05:24.783 --> 00:05:26.535 align:middle line:84%
For people who don't
know this, it's

00:05:26.535 --> 00:05:29.663 align:middle line:84%
owned by Jeff Bezos, the
guy behind amazon.com

00:05:29.663 --> 00:05:31.414 align:middle line:90%
he owns "The Washington Post."

00:05:31.414 --> 00:05:33.457 align:middle line:84%
Since that ownership
switch, there

00:05:33.457 --> 00:05:35.377 align:middle line:90%
has been a change in narrative.

00:05:35.377 --> 00:05:37.337 align:middle line:84%
You can agree or disagree
with the narrative,

00:05:37.337 --> 00:05:39.923 align:middle line:84%
but just to give an example,
"The Washington Post"

00:05:39.923 --> 00:05:43.343 align:middle line:84%
ran a story on their website
calling me an online bully.

00:05:43.343 --> 00:05:45.804 align:middle line:84%
And I couldn't really push back
against that, because there

00:05:45.804 --> 00:05:47.264 align:middle line:90%
is no individual behind it.

00:05:47.264 --> 00:05:49.182 align:middle line:84%
If it was someone like--
if it was Sean Stone,

00:05:49.182 --> 00:05:51.977 align:middle line:84%
I'd say on Twitter, hey, Sean
Stone, why are you saying this?

00:05:51.977 --> 00:05:52.936 align:middle line:90%
And I'd get a response.

00:05:52.936 --> 00:05:56.106 align:middle line:84%
But it was just "The Washington
Post" says that I'm a bully.

00:05:56.106 --> 00:05:58.149 align:middle line:90%
OK, how do we deal with this?

00:05:58.149 --> 00:05:59.317 align:middle line:90%
How is this sourced?

00:05:59.317 --> 00:06:00.694 align:middle line:90%
And, in fact, I wasn't a bully.

00:06:00.694 --> 00:06:02.696 align:middle line:84%
Just reading out the
things in Wikileaks

00:06:02.696 --> 00:06:04.447 align:middle line:90%
doesn't make one a bully.

00:06:04.447 --> 00:06:06.491 align:middle line:84%
But that's what they're
allowed to get away with,

00:06:06.491 --> 00:06:08.618 align:middle line:84%
because they still
have this credibility

00:06:08.618 --> 00:06:11.246 align:middle line:84%
in the eyes of many people--
same with the "New York Times."

00:06:11.246 --> 00:06:13.039 align:middle line:84%
And I think they're
both losing it rapidly.

00:06:13.039 --> 00:06:18.420 align:middle line:84%
Because you start crying wolf
enough times, there's no wolf,

00:06:18.420 --> 00:06:19.796 align:middle line:84%
people aren't
going to trust you.

00:06:19.796 --> 00:06:21.965 align:middle line:84%
Like the online bully thing,
that probably cost them

00:06:21.965 --> 00:06:22.757 align:middle line:90%
some credibility.

00:06:22.757 --> 00:06:25.051 align:middle line:84%
Because people go, oh,
he's criticizing someone

00:06:25.051 --> 00:06:26.636 align:middle line:90%
based on very credible things.

00:06:26.636 --> 00:06:29.139 align:middle line:84%
>> SEAN: Well, I think a lot
of that credibility that people

00:06:29.139 --> 00:06:31.308 align:middle line:84%
give to "The Washington
Post" and "New York Times"

00:06:31.308 --> 00:06:32.558 align:middle line:90%
is oftentimes built on money.

00:06:32.558 --> 00:06:35.353 align:middle line:84%
It's built on the ability
to brand yourself, right?

00:06:35.353 --> 00:06:37.731 align:middle line:84%
And so once you've
created this notion of,

00:06:37.731 --> 00:06:40.775 align:middle line:84%
we have power and money, we are
able to control the narrative--

00:06:40.775 --> 00:06:42.402 align:middle line:84%
and as you say, people
are now shifting

00:06:42.402 --> 00:06:44.404 align:middle line:90%
in terms of their appeal.

00:06:44.404 --> 00:06:46.823 align:middle line:84%
The appeal is more
based on personalities,

00:06:46.823 --> 00:06:50.243 align:middle line:84%
based on having a resonance and
believing, I trust this person,

00:06:50.243 --> 00:06:52.746 align:middle line:84%
I like this person, I'm
more inclined to believe

00:06:52.746 --> 00:06:54.414 align:middle line:90%
that narrative.

00:06:54.414 --> 00:06:56.707 align:middle line:84%
But do you think that what
we're going to see now

00:06:56.707 --> 00:06:59.878 align:middle line:84%
is that Facebook, Twitter,
and these other platforms

00:06:59.878 --> 00:07:01.921 align:middle line:84%
are going to try to
work to basically censor

00:07:01.921 --> 00:07:02.881 align:middle line:90%
the alternative voices?

00:07:02.881 --> 00:07:05.050 align:middle line:84%
>> SEAMAN: Some of them
appear to be heading in that

00:07:05.050 --> 00:07:06.009 align:middle line:90%
direction.

00:07:06.009 --> 00:07:08.845 align:middle line:84%
And they're just going
to lose business-wise.

00:07:08.845 --> 00:07:11.806 align:middle line:84%
Why would I use Facebook
if I know they're starting

00:07:11.806 --> 00:07:13.683 align:middle line:90%
to censor alternative views?

00:07:13.683 --> 00:07:15.393 align:middle line:84%
People used to
log in to Facebook

00:07:15.393 --> 00:07:17.312 align:middle line:84%
to see what their
friends were thinking

00:07:17.312 --> 00:07:19.314 align:middle line:84%
and to see what the
non-mainstream people were

00:07:19.314 --> 00:07:21.274 align:middle line:84%
thinking, at least
some people do that.

00:07:21.274 --> 00:07:24.736 align:middle line:84%
That's the point of Twitter, is
to get these different views.

00:07:24.736 --> 00:07:26.821 align:middle line:10%
And yeah, what I had read--

00:07:26.821 --> 00:07:29.991 align:middle line:10%
I don't know how credible it
is, but Zuckerberg and Facebook

00:07:29.991 --> 00:07:33.078 align:middle line:10%
were considering using
Media Matters for America

00:07:33.078 --> 00:07:36.122 align:middle line:10%
as the third-party vetting
source for what is fake news

00:07:36.122 --> 00:07:37.874 align:middle line:10%
or not.

00:07:37.874 --> 00:07:39.959 align:middle line:84%
I take exception to
that, because the founder

00:07:39.959 --> 00:07:44.464 align:middle line:84%
of Media Matters is David Brock,
a very close Clinton insider.

00:07:44.464 --> 00:07:46.424 align:middle line:84%
This is not a claim that
anybody can push back

00:07:46.424 --> 00:07:47.884 align:middle line:84%
against because
everybody knows it.

00:07:47.884 --> 00:07:49.928 align:middle line:84%
He's very close to
the Clintons, and he's

00:07:49.928 --> 00:07:52.430 align:middle line:84%
very close to some of
the people involved

00:07:52.430 --> 00:07:54.641 align:middle line:84%
in some upcoming
political scandals.

00:07:54.641 --> 00:07:57.602 align:middle line:84%
So they're simply not
credible to judge something

00:07:57.602 --> 00:07:59.104 align:middle line:90%
in an unbiased way.

00:07:59.104 --> 00:08:00.772 align:middle line:84%
We don't want that
on the right, either.

00:08:00.772 --> 00:08:02.691 align:middle line:84%
We don't want some
right-wing think tank

00:08:02.691 --> 00:08:04.401 align:middle line:84%
to tell us what is
news and what is not.

00:08:04.401 --> 00:08:06.528 align:middle line:84%
So why would we want the
left-wing version of that?

00:08:06.528 --> 00:08:08.113 align:middle line:84%
>> SEAN: You don't want Steve
Bannon's group basically

00:08:08.113 --> 00:08:09.489 align:middle line:84%
censoring the news
any more than Brock,

00:08:09.489 --> 00:08:11.741 align:middle line:84%
who is a Super PAC donor
for the Democratic Party.

