So now you can grow
and consume in Maine.

00:16:32.408 --> 00:16:34.285 align:middle line:84%
So it definitely seems
like it's happening.

00:16:34.285 --> 00:16:36.787 align:middle line:84%
The argument against
it has fallen the way.

00:16:36.787 --> 00:16:38.706 align:middle line:90%
I've smoked hundreds of times.

00:16:38.706 --> 00:16:41.667 align:middle line:84%
I haven't noticed any
reduction in intelligence.

00:16:41.667 --> 00:16:44.712 align:middle line:84%
I know many successful
type-A people who smoke,

00:16:44.712 --> 00:16:46.339 align:middle line:84%
and I think we are
simply lied to.

00:16:46.339 --> 00:16:47.882 align:middle line:84%
I think it's easier
to just say, hey,

00:16:47.882 --> 00:16:50.259 align:middle line:84%
we were lied to, than
to continue to come up

00:16:50.259 --> 00:16:51.844 align:middle line:90%
with all these explanations.

00:16:51.844 --> 00:16:54.472 align:middle line:84%
I'll talk to somebody every
once in a while in Alabama

00:16:54.472 --> 00:16:57.266 align:middle line:84%
or Georgia, and they give me
this reasoning where it's like,

00:16:57.266 --> 00:16:59.977 align:middle line:84%
no, no, no, we can't have it
here because of A, B, and C.

00:16:59.977 --> 00:17:01.395 align:middle line:84%
I'm like, no, it's
the same plant.

00:17:01.395 --> 00:17:03.439 align:middle line:84%
It's not any different in
Colorado or California.

00:17:03.439 --> 00:17:04.440 align:middle line:90%
It's the same thing.

00:17:04.440 --> 00:17:05.858 align:middle line:84%
So we have to look
at the science,

00:17:05.858 --> 00:17:07.443 align:middle line:90%
as that MD was telling me.

00:17:07.443 --> 00:17:11.739 align:middle line:84%
There are these amazing
biopharmacology properties

00:17:11.739 --> 00:17:13.866 align:middle line:90%
that don't exist anywhere else.

00:17:13.866 --> 00:17:14.951 align:middle line:90%
And people are adults.

00:17:14.951 --> 00:17:16.493 align:middle line:90%
They deserve the best treatment.

00:17:16.493 --> 00:17:20.039 align:middle line:84%
And they deserve that
spiritual experience.

00:17:20.039 --> 00:17:22.791 align:middle line:84%
>> SEAN: Even anti-carcinogenic
purposes, as I understand it,

00:17:22.791 --> 00:17:24.919 align:middle line:84%
like hemp oil, for example,
is supposed to be great

00:17:24.919 --> 00:17:26.087 align:middle line:90%
for combating cancers.

00:17:26.087 --> 00:17:27.797 align:middle line:84%
>> SEAMAN: That's what
people are saying.

00:17:27.797 --> 00:17:29.423 align:middle line:84%
And anecdotally,
there's a lot of stuff

00:17:29.423 --> 00:17:32.176 align:middle line:84%
that it's great for--
seizures, great for depression.

00:17:32.176 --> 00:17:33.970 align:middle line:84%
People have to
realize for many years

00:17:33.970 --> 00:17:35.930 align:middle line:84%
the only studies that
were being funded

00:17:35.930 --> 00:17:37.556 align:middle line:90%
were ones trying to prove harm.

00:17:37.556 --> 00:17:40.142 align:middle line:84%
Whenever you do that, you're not
going to find the good stuff.

00:17:40.142 --> 00:17:44.063 align:middle line:84%
Now that we have a thawing
of views on weed, let's look.

00:17:44.063 --> 00:17:45.439 align:middle line:84%
Does it actually
help depression?

00:17:45.439 --> 00:17:46.816 align:middle line:90%
Does it actually help IBS?

00:17:46.816 --> 00:17:50.069 align:middle line:84%
Does it actually help with
anti-cancer properties?

00:17:50.069 --> 00:17:52.029 align:middle line:90%
And so far the answer--

00:17:52.029 --> 00:17:54.782 align:middle line:84%
it's a cautious answer,
but it seems to be yes.

00:17:54.782 --> 00:17:57.410 align:middle line:84%
>> SEAN: But there obviously is
one concern I know from smaller

00:17:57.410 --> 00:17:58.244 align:middle line:90%
growers.

00:17:58.244 --> 00:18:01.539 align:middle line:84%
As they're seeing
legalization of marijuana,

00:18:01.539 --> 00:18:04.125 align:middle line:84%
potentially you're going to see
basically the big agribusiness

00:18:04.125 --> 00:18:04.583 align:middle line:90%
coming in.

00:18:04.583 --> 00:18:06.043 align:middle line:84%
The Monsantos of
the world they see

00:18:06.043 --> 00:18:11.590 align:middle line:84%
coming in and putting their
herbicides and pesticides

00:18:11.590 --> 00:18:14.760 align:middle line:84%
into the plants themselves,
controlling the industry.

00:18:14.760 --> 00:18:19.265 align:middle line:84%
Is that a potential danger
from this legalization process?

00:18:19.265 --> 00:18:21.600 align:middle line:84%
>> SEAMAN: I think there are
always dangers from the big

00:18:21.600 --> 00:18:23.060 align:middle line:90%
money taking over.

00:18:23.060 --> 00:18:24.770 align:middle line:90%
But I'll give you an example.

00:18:24.770 --> 00:18:27.565 align:middle line:84%
In Maryland, they have
already passed medical laws,

00:18:27.565 --> 00:18:29.233 align:middle line:84%
but there has been
this big holdup.

00:18:29.233 --> 00:18:32.570 align:middle line:84%
They don't actually have any
dispensaries serving weed yet,

00:18:32.570 --> 00:18:34.488 align:middle line:84%
even though it was
passed years ago.

00:18:34.488 --> 00:18:36.824 align:middle line:84%
The reason why is that the
Maryland Cannabis Commission,

00:18:36.824 --> 00:18:40.786 align:middle line:84%
from what I understand, they're
facing potential lawsuits

00:18:40.786 --> 00:18:43.456 align:middle line:84%
from minority
groups in Maryland.

00:18:43.456 --> 00:18:46.792 align:middle line:84%
Basically a bunch of black
business owners are saying,

00:18:46.792 --> 00:18:50.087 align:middle line:84%
we didn't get the right number
of licenses in the bidding

00:18:50.087 --> 00:18:50.880 align:middle line:90%
process.

00:18:50.880 --> 00:18:53.507 align:middle line:84%
Minority-owned
businesses were shut out,

00:18:53.507 --> 00:18:56.761 align:middle line:84%
and it was just big cannabis
that got the contracts.

00:18:56.761 --> 00:18:58.721 align:middle line:84%
And so they're pushing
back against it.

00:18:58.721 --> 00:19:01.515 align:middle line:84%
And I personally disagree
with them in this case.

00:19:01.515 --> 00:19:04.226 align:middle line:84%
It's great if you can
make money from marijuana.

00:19:04.226 --> 00:19:05.644 align:middle line:90%
More power to you.

00:19:05.644 --> 00:19:07.772 align:middle line:84%
You can do it legally
and hire people.

00:19:07.772 --> 00:19:12.193 align:middle line:84%
Here in Colorado, I think
16,500 jobs have been added

00:19:12.193 --> 00:19:14.362 align:middle line:90%
due to the legalization thing.

00:19:14.362 --> 00:19:16.906 align:middle line:84%
So, great-- but I don't
think the primary purpose

00:19:16.906 --> 00:19:19.992 align:middle line:84%
of legalization should be to
make money for entrepreneurs.

00:19:19.992 --> 00:19:22.995 align:middle line:84%
I think we need to get it
decriminalized and available

00:19:22.995 --> 00:19:24.372 align:middle line:90%
ASAP.

00:19:24.372 --> 00:19:26.791 align:middle line:84%
And look, if Monsanto is
going to make all the money

00:19:26.791 --> 00:19:29.710 align:middle line:84%
or Coca-Cola is going to launch
some weed product or something,

00:19:29.710 --> 00:19:30.920 align:middle line:84%
then that's going to
happen, and you're not

00:19:30.920 --> 00:19:32.213 align:middle line:90%
going to be able to stop it.

00:19:32.213 --> 00:19:34.465 align:middle line:84%
But I just don't want people
going to prison for it,

00:19:34.465 --> 00:19:37.593 align:middle line:84%
and I just don't want cancer
patients and arthritis patients

00:19:37.593 --> 00:19:39.762 align:middle line:84%
and people with seizures
to not be able to get it

00:19:39.762 --> 00:19:42.223 align:middle line:84%
because somebody is
saying, hey, the big guys

00:19:42.223 --> 00:19:43.557 align:middle line:90%
are crushing me out of this.

00:19:43.557 --> 00:19:45.017 align:middle line:84%
This is not the
only industry where

00:19:45.017 --> 00:19:47.645 align:middle line:84%
the big money moves in and
pushes out the craft beer,

00:19:47.645 --> 00:19:48.437 align:middle line:90%
right?

00:19:48.437 --> 00:19:49.397 align:middle line:90%
We see this in alcohol.

00:19:49.397 --> 00:19:50.523 align:middle line:90%
It's the same thing.

00:19:50.523 --> 00:19:52.274 align:middle line:84%
So I think we need
to consider that,

00:19:52.274 --> 00:19:54.318 align:middle line:84%
but I just want to see
legal as soon as possible.

00:19:54.318 --> 00:19:56.153 align:middle line:84%
>> SEAN: Yeah, and I
totally agree with you,

00:19:56.153 --> 00:19:58.656 align:middle line:84%
especially with the prison
population where half of it is

00:19:58.656 --> 00:20:01.033 align:middle line:84%
based on nonviolent crimes,
including things like

00:20:01.033 --> 00:20:01.826 align:middle line:90%
marijuana.

00:20:01.826 --> 00:20:05.037 align:middle line:84%
So you mentioned earlier
about the US dollar,

00:20:05.037 --> 00:20:07.665 align:middle line:84%
obviously the strongest
currency in the world

00:20:07.665 --> 00:20:09.959 align:middle line:90%
over this post-World War II era.

00:20:09.959 --> 00:20:13.963 align:middle line:84%
And yet there is this new
Bitcoin online currency

00:20:13.963 --> 00:20:16.966 align:middle line:90%
that's now circulating.

00:20:16.966 --> 00:20:17.758 align:middle line:90%
What is Bitcoin?

00:20:17.758 --> 00:20:20.803 align:middle line:84%
And how will it
compare ultimately

00:20:20.803 --> 00:20:23.597 align:middle line:84%
to the dollar and potentially
transcend the dollar?

00:20:23.597 --> 00:20:25.933 align:middle line:84%
>> SEAMAN: Yeah, this relates
to your idea of reality

00:20:25.933 --> 00:20:28.811 align:middle line:84%
fracturing, of consensus
reality fracturing.

00:20:28.811 --> 00:20:30.896 align:middle line:84%
Because you need a strong
consensus for something

00:20:30.896 --> 00:20:32.606 align:middle line:90%
like the dollar to work.

00:20:32.606 --> 00:20:35.317 align:middle line:84%
It's the fiat currency
for the United States.

00:20:35.317 --> 00:20:37.069 align:middle line:84%
So a good way of
thinking about it is it's

00:20:37.069 --> 00:20:39.363 align:middle line:84%
like an arcade
token when you enter

00:20:39.363 --> 00:20:41.282 align:middle line:90%
the arcade, known as the US.

00:20:41.282 --> 00:20:44.410 align:middle line:84%
You hit US soil, you
have to use our tokens

00:20:44.410 --> 00:20:47.538 align:middle line:84%
to pay for everything from
parking to food, et cetera.

00:20:47.538 --> 00:20:50.499 align:middle line:84%
You go to the EU, you
have to use the euro token

00:20:50.499 --> 00:20:51.584 align:middle line:90%
to do something there.

00:20:51.584 --> 00:20:54.587 align:middle line:84%
So there is a rarity that builds
up over time for these tokens

00:20:54.587 --> 00:20:56.464 align:middle line:84%
because we need
them to do anything.

00:20:56.464 --> 00:20:58.507 align:middle line:84%
But when you look at
the creation process,

00:20:58.507 --> 00:21:01.135 align:middle line:84%
it is literally just an
old woman in New York City,

00:21:01.135 --> 00:21:02.595 align:middle line:84%
in the case of the
Federal Reserve.

00:21:02.595 --> 00:21:05.639 align:middle line:84%
It's Janet Yellen and
her board of governors.

00:21:05.639 --> 00:21:08.225 align:middle line:84%
They decide when to create
more of these tokens.

00:21:08.225 --> 00:21:12.438 align:middle line:84%
You look at the EU, it's Draghi
and his peers in Brussels,

00:21:12.438 --> 00:21:15.441 align:middle line:84%
I believe, or in
Belgium, saying, look,

00:21:15.441 --> 00:21:17.902 align:middle line:84%
we're going to create this
many new euro over the next two

00:21:17.902 --> 00:21:18.694 align:middle line:90%
years.

00:21:18.694 --> 00:21:19.653 align:middle line:90%
Here you go.

00:21:19.653 --> 00:21:21.530 align:middle line:84%
That's just a human
being deciding something.

00:21:21.530 --> 00:21:23.407 align:middle line:84%
It's just an
unelected politician

00:21:23.407 --> 00:21:24.909 align:middle line:90%
coming up with something.

00:21:24.909 --> 00:21:27.953 align:middle line:84%
Bitcoin was invented
some eight years ago.

00:21:27.953 --> 00:21:30.915 align:middle line:84%
And like the dollar, like
the euro, just a rare token.

00:21:30.915 --> 00:21:32.249 align:middle line:90%
It's called a bitcoin.

00:21:32.249 --> 00:21:33.918 align:middle line:90%
It's not called a US dollar.

00:21:33.918 --> 00:21:35.586 align:middle line:84%
But he put some
cool limits on it.

00:21:35.586 --> 00:21:39.548 align:middle line:84%
There are only 21 million
coins that will ever exist.

00:21:39.548 --> 00:21:44.094 align:middle line:84%
And right now, about 16.5
million coins have been mined.

00:21:44.094 --> 00:21:46.347 align:middle line:84%
And so he created a
software program that

00:21:46.347 --> 00:21:49.016 align:middle line:90%
mimics the psychology of gold.

00:21:49.016 --> 00:21:51.310 align:middle line:84%
Gold always emerged
throughout history

00:21:51.310 --> 00:21:53.896 align:middle line:84%
as a really good form of money
because it's a rare token, just

00:21:53.896 --> 00:21:54.980 align:middle line:90%
like the dollar.

00:21:54.980 --> 00:21:57.107 align:middle line:84%
But it's not something
that's political.

00:21:57.107 --> 00:22:00.528 align:middle line:84%
When you have a piece of
gold, that was a fair process,

00:22:00.528 --> 00:22:02.696 align:middle line:84%
because someone somewhere
had to mine for it.

00:22:02.696 --> 00:22:05.950 align:middle line:84%
Even if it was 500 years
ago in some king's camp,

00:22:05.950 --> 00:22:07.952 align:middle line:84%
it was mined at one
point, and there

00:22:07.952 --> 00:22:10.829 align:middle line:84%
is an exchange of labor
for this form of money.

00:22:10.829 --> 00:22:12.248 align:middle line:84%
With the dollar
and the euro, that

00:22:12.248 --> 00:22:14.416 align:middle line:84%
doesn't exist, because
they're creating it

00:22:14.416 --> 00:22:15.876 align:middle line:90%
through political decree.

00:22:15.876 --> 00:22:19.755 align:middle line:84%
Bitcoin brings us back to that
fair, older version of money,

00:22:19.755 --> 00:22:22.550 align:middle line:84%
because every token of bitcoin
that's out there, someone

00:22:22.550 --> 00:22:23.801 align:middle line:90%
had to mine for it.

00:22:23.801 --> 00:22:25.553 align:middle line:84%
Someone's computer
in their basement

00:22:25.553 --> 00:22:26.887 align:middle line:90%
or in their dorm room--

00:22:26.887 --> 00:22:28.764 align:middle line:84%
or now it's actually
professional facilities

00:22:28.764 --> 00:22:30.182 align:middle line:90%
in a lot of cases.

00:22:30.182 --> 00:22:33.018 align:middle line:84%
Some server somewhere
mined for that coin

00:22:33.018 --> 00:22:35.980 align:middle line:84%
and expended labor and
time, computing time,

00:22:35.980 --> 00:22:37.189 align:middle line:90%
to earn that coin.

00:22:37.189 --> 00:22:38.148 align:middle line:90%
So it's a neat idea.

00:22:38.148 --> 00:22:38.941 align:middle line:90%
>> SEAN: Right.

00:22:38.941 --> 00:22:41.986 align:middle line:84%
So the idea is that there's a
fixed amount of this bitcoin.

00:22:41.986 --> 00:22:46.240 align:middle line:84%
But what makes it different from
just any of the currency that

00:22:46.240 --> 00:22:47.616 align:middle line:84%
floats basically
on the exchange,

00:22:47.616 --> 00:22:50.911 align:middle line:84%
in terms of how in-demand
it is raises the value

00:22:50.911 --> 00:22:52.079 align:middle line:90%
or splinters it?

00:22:52.079 --> 00:22:52.955 align:middle line:90%
>> SEAMAN: Sure.

00:22:52.955 --> 00:22:54.540 align:middle line:84%
Well, there are
technical differences.

00:22:54.540 --> 00:22:58.335 align:middle line:84%
Whoever created it-- Satoshi
Nakamoto is the pseudonym he

00:22:58.335 --> 00:22:59.378 align:middle line:90%
used--

00:22:59.378 --> 00:23:02.756 align:middle line:84%
the rarity is enforced by this
thing called the block chain.

00:23:02.756 --> 00:23:05.968 align:middle line:84%
So there is a ledger of every
single Bitcoin transaction,

00:23:05.968 --> 00:23:08.971 align:middle line:84%
going back to the very
first ones in 2009.

00:23:08.971 --> 00:23:12.766 align:middle line:84%
And every block of transactions
builds of the prior block.

00:23:12.766 --> 00:23:15.728 align:middle line:84%
I won't get into the
details, but basically it's

00:23:15.728 --> 00:23:18.647 align:middle line:84%
like a big puzzle board,
where the next puzzle

00:23:18.647 --> 00:23:20.566 align:middle line:84%
piece doesn't fit
in unless you've

00:23:20.566 --> 00:23:22.318 align:middle line:90%
solved the previous puzzle.

00:23:22.318 --> 00:23:25.821 align:middle line:84%
So every block every 10
minutes is reconciled,

00:23:25.821 --> 00:23:27.823 align:middle line:84%
all those transactions,
and then it

00:23:27.823 --> 00:23:30.117 align:middle line:84%
becomes a part of the permanent
record in this ledger,

00:23:30.117 --> 00:23:31.327 align:middle line:90%
this block chain.

00:23:31.327 --> 00:23:33.162 align:middle line:84%
So that's how they
keep it rare, is

00:23:33.162 --> 00:23:35.956 align:middle line:84%
there's no introduction
of counterfeit bitcoin.

00:23:35.956 --> 00:23:37.791 align:middle line:84%
There's no increase
in the money supply.

00:23:37.791 --> 00:23:40.294 align:middle line:84%
It's still going to be
a max of 21 million.

00:23:40.294 --> 00:23:42.963 align:middle line:84%
>> SEAN: We've seen historically
people have cornered the silver

00:23:42.963 --> 00:23:44.465 align:middle line:84%
market, cornered
the gold market.

00:23:44.465 --> 00:23:46.759 align:middle line:84%
Why can't a George
Soros or Bill Gates

00:23:46.759 --> 00:23:49.762 align:middle line:84%
go in and basically with his
minions buy up all the bitcoins

00:23:49.762 --> 00:23:51.972 align:middle line:84%
and corner the
market and basically

00:23:51.972 --> 00:23:53.557 align:middle line:90%
control the price at that point?

00:23:53.557 --> 00:23:55.559 align:middle line:84%
>> SEAMAN: I think that
could definitely happen,

00:23:55.559 --> 00:23:56.769 align:middle line:90%
at least temporarily.

00:23:56.769 --> 00:23:58.729 align:middle line:90%
There's no control against that.

00:23:58.729 --> 00:24:01.565 align:middle line:84%
What's so neat about bitcoin is
that we just see all the terms.

00:24:01.565 --> 00:24:03.192 align:middle line:90%
We know how many exist.

00:24:03.192 --> 00:24:05.110 align:middle line:84%
We can see them moving
around the world thanks

00:24:05.110 --> 00:24:06.654 align:middle line:90%
to that block chain innovation.

00:24:06.654 --> 00:24:08.864 align:middle line:84%
So there's more transparency
than with the dollar.

00:24:08.864 --> 00:24:11.200 align:middle line:84%
But the main thing is the
difference in how it's created.

00:24:11.200 --> 00:24:15.829 align:middle line:84%
You have individuals voluntarily
deciding to mine for bitcoin

00:24:15.829 --> 00:24:17.623 align:middle line:84%
because they think
they'll make a profit

00:24:17.623 --> 00:24:19.667 align:middle line:84%
or because they're
ideologically aligned

00:24:19.667 --> 00:24:21.168 align:middle line:90%
with government-free money.

00:24:21.168 --> 00:24:22.753 align:middle line:84%
Whatever their
reason is, they're

00:24:22.753 --> 00:24:25.047 align:middle line:90%
voluntarily deciding to use it.

00:24:25.047 --> 00:24:26.465 align:middle line:84%
And I think that's
the difference.

00:24:26.465 --> 00:24:28.592 align:middle line:84%
When I was born
in this country, I

00:24:28.592 --> 00:24:31.345 align:middle line:84%
didn't have a say in whether
or not all of my labor

00:24:31.345 --> 00:24:34.181 align:middle line:90%
would be represented by dollars.

00:24:34.181 --> 00:24:35.057 align:middle line:90%
I was born here.

00:24:35.057 --> 00:24:36.558 align:middle line:84%
It's got to be
represented that way.

00:24:36.558 --> 00:24:39.019 align:middle line:84%
Except Janet Yellen-- I've
never met her before--

00:24:39.019 --> 00:24:41.689 align:middle line:84%
I don't necessarily agree
with her views on the world.

00:24:41.689 --> 00:24:43.315 align:middle line:84%
So why should that
be my currency?

00:24:43.315 --> 00:24:43.607 align:middle line:90%
>> SEAN: Right.

00:24:43.607 --> 00:24:45.401 align:middle line:84%
So the idea is this is a way of
challenging the Federal Reserve

00:24:45.401 --> 00:24:46.235 align:middle line:90%
System.

00:24:46.235 --> 00:24:48.570 align:middle line:84%
And ideally, there will
be more bitcoin-type

